                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d259">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.9414/9: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Legation in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-09T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 9, 1935—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 9—3:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>199. My June 28, 10 a.m. and Canton’s despatch June 5. Administrative Vice
                    Minister of the Navy tells me confidentially that Japanese fishermen and seaweed
                    hunters frequently and without right visit Pratas Reef (Tungshatao) in motor
                    launches but have not attempted to remain thereon and that, contrary to press
                    and other reports, no Japanese naval vessel has been there for a very long
                    time.</p>
                <p>To the Legation and the Department. To Tokyo by mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
